{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:20:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14118"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14118"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.05,0.01,0.64,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6798"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52751"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6798"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14118"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38126"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2917"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52751"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of swelling around his eyes and legs. He reports that his urine output has decreased, and his urine appears frothy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is periorbital and pedal oedema. Abdominal examination reveals mild ascites. Investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: 4+ protein, no blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin: 18 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 40 \u00b5mol/L (20-60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol: 7.2 mmol/L (2.8-4.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectron microscopy reveals foot process effacement with a lack of findings on light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Membranous nephropathy","IgA nephropathy","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Minimal change disease","Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of nephrotic syndrome, including proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidemia, and edema. The most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eminimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children and young adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinimal change disease is characterised by foot process effacement on electron microscopy with normal light microscopy findings, exactly as described in this case. The patient\u0027s age, acute onset of symptoms, and lack of hematuria also support this diagnosis. Minimal change disease typically has an excellent prognosis and responds well to corticosteroid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is also a cause of nephrotic syndrome, but it typically affects older adults and would show thickening of the glomerular basement membrane on electron microscopy, which is not mentioned here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E are more likely to present with hematuria and would show IgA deposits on immunofluorescence, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal segmental glomerulosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly to minimal change disease but would typically show focal and segmental sclerosis on light microscopy, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the patient\u0027s age, presentation with nephrotic syndrome, and characteristic electron microscopy findings strongly support the diagnosis of minimal change disease. The next step in management would typically involve initiating corticosteroid therapy and monitoring for response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Minimal change disease is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children and young adults, characterized by foot process effacement on electron microscopy and normal light microscopy findings.","The classic presentation of nephrotic syndrome includes proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidemia, and edema.","Minimal change disease typically has an excellent prognosis and responds well to corticosteroid therapy."],"references":["Zamora G, Pearson-Shaver AL. Minimal Change Disease. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560639/","Vivarelli M, Massella L, Ruggiero B, Emma F. Minimal Change Disease. Clinical Journal of the American Society of Nephrology. 2017;12(2). Available at: https://journals.lww.com/cjasn/fulltext/2017/02000/minimal_change_disease.17.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14118"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T14:08:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T21:55:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6798"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52751"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1086"},"attributes":{"